         <h1>Donald Swann, 70, A British Composer And Musical Comic </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>Donald Swann , a composer , pianist and entertainer who performed as half of the Flanders and Swann team , which brought quirky British wit to Broadway with " At the Drop of a Hat " in 1959 , died on Wednesday in Trinity Hospice in London . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 70 . <br><blue>3</blue>The cause was prostate cancer , said Lyn Smith , a friend . <br><blue>4</blue>" At the Drop of a Hat " opened in London in 1956 and , with its sequel , " At the Drop of Another Hat " ( which came to Broadway in 1966 ) , toured the world for 11 years . <br><blue>5</blue>The show was a celebration of impish wit , wry observation and a generosity of spirit relieved by the occasional barb . <br><blue>6</blue>Mr. Swann was the gentleman at the piano wearing glasses and a Cheshire-cat grin ; Mr. Flanders was the one with the beard , who , disabled with polio , used a wheelchair . <br><blue>7</blue>' Having a Whale of a Time ' During the show 's West End run , one critic described Mr. Swann as " the complete amateur , a tight crescent smile always adorning his small , neat , shining face . " <br><blue>8</blue>" His piano approach , " the critic continued , " is ludicrous , elbows whirling about , the parlor performer to the life having a whale of a time . " <br><blue>9</blue>With tongues firmly in cheek , the performers essayed flights of light verse , including a comic ballad about the London bus . <br><blue>10</blue>They sang in Greek , Russian and Latin , and tossed off songs celebrating the wart hog , the wompom , the gnu , the armadillo and the hippopotamus . <br><blue>11</blue>Their hippopotamus song went , in part , " Mud , mud , glorious mud , there 's nothing quite like it for cooling the blood . " <br><blue>12</blue>On Broadway , where the show ran for 215 performances , " At the Drop of a Hat " had a Piccadilly backdrop created by the artist Al Hirschfeld , and Big Ben struck 9 o'clock as the show started . <br><blue>13</blue>Donald Ibrahim Swann was born in Wales on Sept. 30 , 1923 . <br><blue>14</blue>He was educated at Westminster School and Christ Church College , Oxford , where he took part in theatrical revues with Kenneth Tynan . <br><blue>15</blue>He was a conscientious objector during World War II and did relief work in Britain , Egypt and Palestine . <br><blue>16</blue>Returning to Oxford , he wrote revues and songs with Mr. Flanders , who was the lyricist . <br><blue>17</blue>" At the Drop of a Hat " began when the team performed their own compositions for friends at parties . <br><blue>18</blue>The partnership ended in 1967 , although the performers remained friends until the death of Mr. Flanders in 1975 . <br><blue>19</blue>Solo Shows During the 1970 's and 80 's Mr. Swann performed solo shows in Britain and around the world . <br><blue>20</blue>He befriended C. S. Lewis and wrote a lyrical opera , " Perelandra , " for him ; he also wrote a song cycle , " The Road Goes Ever On , " for another friend , the author J. R. R. Tolkien . <br><hr><br><blue>1(4)</blue>: <m_str>the Flanders</m_str> (1_15) 	<m_str>Mr. Flanders</m_str> (18_16) 	<m_str>Mr. Flanders</m_str> (6_16) 	<m_str>Mr. Flanders , who was the lyricist</m_str> (16_11) 	<br><blue>2(2)</blue>: <m_str>the critic</m_str> (8_7) 	<m_str>one critic</m_str> (7_17) 	<br><blue>3(2)</blue>: <m_str>the world</m_str> (19_19) 	<m_str>the world</m_str> (4_38) 	<br><blue>4(12)</blue>: <m_str>Donald Ibrahim Swann</m_str> (13_1) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (15_1) 	<m_str>Swann</m_str> (1_18) 	<m_str>him</m_str> (20_17) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (20_19) 	<m_str>Mr. Swann</m_str> (6_1) 	<m_str>Mr. Swann as `` the complete amateur , a tight crescent smile always adorning his small , neat , shining face</m_str> (7_20) 	<m_str>Mr. Swann</m_str> (19_10) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (14_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (16_5) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (20_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (14_15) 	<br><blue>5(4)</blue>: <m_str>the performers</m_str> (9_7) 	<m_str>They</m_str> (10_1) 	<m_str>the performers</m_str> (18_8) 	<m_str>Their</m_str> (11_1) 	<br><blue>6(3)</blue>: <m_str>London</m_str> (1_47) 	<m_str>London</m_str> (9_21) 	<m_str>London</m_str> (4_11) 	<br><blue>7(4)</blue>: <m_str>the show 's</m_str> (7_10) 	<m_str>the show</m_str> (12_5) 	<m_str>the show</m_str> (12_38) 	<m_str>The show</m_str> (5_1) 	<br><blue>8(2)</blue>: <m_str>it</m_str> (11_22) 	<m_str>Mud , mud , glorious mud</m_str> (11_10) 	<br><blue>9(2)</blue>: <m_str>Broadway</m_str> (1_27) 	<m_str>Broadway</m_str> (12_2) 	<br><blue>10(2)</blue>: <m_str>his</m_str> (7_34) 	<m_str>His</m_str> (8_2) 	<hr><br> gender:male	ethnicity:european<br>         </p>
